<h1>🇵🇬 Papua New Guinea — Complete Country Guide</h1>

<h2>🌏 Introduction</h2>

<p>
<strong>Papua New Guinea</strong>, officially known as the <strong>Independent State of Papua New Guinea</strong>, is a country located in the <strong>southwestern Pacific Ocean</strong>. It occupies the eastern half of the island of New Guinea and includes hundreds of surrounding islands.
</p>

<p>
Papua New Guinea is famous for its incredible cultural diversity, tropical rainforests, active volcanoes, coral reefs, rich wildlife, and traditional tribal societies. It is one of the world's most biologically and culturally diverse countries.
</p>

<p>
Today, Papua New Guinea's economy is supported by mining, oil and gas, agriculture, forestry, fisheries, tourism, and natural resource exports.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>📍 Capital City</h2>

<p>
The capital city of Papua New Guinea is <strong>Port Moresby</strong>.
</p>

<p>
Port Moresby is the country's political, economic, and administrative center. It is also the largest city and serves as the main international gateway.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏙 Major Cities</h2>

<ul>
<li>Port Moresby — Capital city</li>
<li>Lae — Industrial and port city</li>
<li>Mount Hagen — Highlands commercial center</li>
<li>Madang — Tourism and shipping hub</li>
<li>Goroka — Agricultural center</li>
<li>Kokopo — East New Britain capital</li>
<li>Kimbe — Palm oil production center</li>
<li>Wewak — Historic coastal city</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>👥 Population</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea has a population of approximately <strong>10 million</strong> people.
</p>

<p>
The population consists mainly of Melanesian peoples with hundreds of distinct ethnic groups, making it one of the world's most culturally diverse countries.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🗣 Languages</h2>

<p>
The official languages are <strong>English</strong>, <strong>Tok Pisin</strong>, <strong>Hiri Motu</strong>, and hundreds of indigenous languages.
</p>

<p>
Papua New Guinea has over <strong>800 living languages</strong>, more than any other country in the world.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>💰 Currency</h2>

<p>
The official currency is the <strong>Papua New Guinean Kina (PGK)</strong>.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🌍 Geography</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea covers approximately <strong>462,840 square kilometers</strong>. It features mountains, volcanoes, tropical rainforests, rivers, islands, coral reefs, and fertile valleys.
</p>

<ul>
<li>New Guinea Island</li>
<li>Bismarck Archipelago</li>
<li>Sepik River</li>
<li>Mount Wilhelm</li>
<li>Owen Stanley Range</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🌦 Climate</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea has a <strong>tropical climate</strong> with warm temperatures throughout the year. Rainfall is abundant, especially in rainforest regions.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏛 History</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea has been inhabited for over 40,000 years. European explorers arrived during the 16th century, and the country later came under German, British, and Australian administration.
</p>

<p>
Papua New Guinea gained independence from Australia on <strong>16 September 1975</strong> and became an independent member of the Commonwealth.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>📈 Economy</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea has a resource-rich economy driven by mining, petroleum, natural gas, agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and tourism.
</p>

<p>
Gold, copper, liquefied natural gas (LNG), coffee, cocoa, and palm oil are among the country's major economic products.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏭 Industries</h2>

<ul>
<li>Mining</li>
<li>Oil & Natural Gas</li>
<li>Agriculture</li>
<li>Forestry</li>
<li>Fishing</li>
<li>Tourism</li>
<li>Manufacturing</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>⛏ Natural Resources</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea possesses rich deposits of gold, copper, silver, oil, natural gas, timber, fisheries, fertile farmland, and hydroelectric potential.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>💻 Technology & Innovation</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea is gradually expanding telecommunications, renewable energy, digital banking, internet services, mobile technology, and educational technology across the country.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏙 Urban Development</h2>

<p>
Port Moresby, Lae, Mount Hagen, and other major cities continue developing with improved highways, ports, airports, hospitals, schools, housing projects, and commercial infrastructure.
</p>

<hr>
<hr>

<h2>🏛 Government</h2>

<p>
<strong>Papua New Guinea</strong> is a <strong>constitutional parliamentary democracy</strong> and a <strong>Commonwealth realm</strong>. The King of the United Kingdom is the Head of State and is represented by the Governor-General, while the Prime Minister is the Head of Government.
</p>

<p>
The government consists of Executive, Legislative, and Judicial branches. The National Parliament makes laws, while the Supreme Court is the country's highest judicial authority.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🌍 Foreign Relations</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea maintains diplomatic relations with countries around the world and is a member of the United Nations (UN), Commonwealth of Nations, Pacific Islands Forum (PIF), APEC, and other international organizations.
</p>

<p>
The country works closely with Australia, New Zealand, Japan, China, Indonesia, and Pacific nations in trade, education, security, environmental protection, and regional development.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🙏 Religion</h2>

<p>
Christianity is the dominant religion in Papua New Guinea. Most people belong to Protestant or Roman Catholic churches, while traditional indigenous beliefs are still practiced in some communities.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🦜 Wildlife</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea is one of the world's richest biodiversity hotspots, with thousands of unique plant and animal species.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Birds-of-Paradise</li>
<li>Tree Kangaroos</li>
<li>Cassowaries</li>
<li>Saltwater Crocodiles</li>
<li>Sea Turtles</li>
<li>Cuscus</li>
<li>Colorful Coral Reef Fish</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🏞 Environment & Climate Challenges</h2>

<p>
Papua New Guinea faces environmental challenges including deforestation, illegal logging, climate change, volcanic activity, earthquakes, and rising sea levels.
</p>

<p>
The government continues to protect rainforests, wildlife, coral reefs, and national parks through conservation programs.
</p>

<hr>

